'''George Thomas Baxter''' is an attorney who fought for the rights of victims of [[AIDS]] and won the landmark verdict against the blood industry for allowing the United States blood supply to be contaminated with AIDS in the early 1980s.<ref>Hanley, Robert. [https://www.nytimes.com/1996/06/05/nyregion/blood-bank-is-held-liable-in-aids-case.html "Blood Bank Is Held Liable in AIDS Case"], ''[[The New York Times]]''. June 5, 1996. Accessed December 30, 2017. "Mr. Snyder's lawyer, George T. Baxter, of Ridgewood, N.J., said Mr. Snyder and his wife, Roslyn, who now live in Florida, were elated by the decision."</ref><ref>[http://www.NJLJ.Com AIDS Victims Win Fight for Blood Bank Discovery] 128 N.J.L.J. Index Page 1075, New Jersey Law Journal, Thursday, August 8, 1991</ref><ref>"Widow's AIDS Suit Going To Trial" Herald & News, Saturday, February 27, 1999</ref> A resident of [[Ridgewood, New Jersey]], Baxter was born in [[Passaic, New Jersey]] and graduated from [[Rutgers Law School]] in 1983.

==Snyder v. American Association of Blood Banks==
In the landmark case [http://leagle.com/decision/1996413144NJ269_1278.xml/SNYDER%20v.%20AMERICAN%20ASS'N%20OF%20BLOOD%20BANKS/ ''Snyder v. American Association of Blood Banks'', 144 N.J. 269 (1996)] the New Jersey Supreme Court affirmed the only jury verdict in the country finding that the blood bankers were negligent and  concern over the cost of donor testing  caused his client to be infected from contaminated blood.<ref>{{Citation | title=State's Top Court holds blood bank group liable for HIV testing in 80's | newspaper=The Star-Ledger | date=June 5, 1996}}</ref>  The evidence from the Snyder trial helped fuel the Congressional Investigation by the Subcommittee of Blood Safety into the Federal [[Food and Drug Administration]]'s regulators and blood bankers  that resulted in people getting AIDS tainted blood in the early 1980s.<ref>"Blood Supply Safety: Hearings Before the Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigation of the House of Representatives Committee on Energy and Commerce (Blood Supply Safety III), 103rd Cong., 1 st Sess., at 1 (1 993)(statement of Congressman Dingell)</ref> Baxter in fighting for the rights of patients infected with AIDS from contaminated blood won the right to donor discovery in ''Snyder v. Makhijan'', 244 N.J. Super 281 (App. Div. 1990) which defined the rights of people infected by contaminated blood to sue the blood bankers.<ref>{{Citation | title=AIDS-Infected Can Question Blood Donors | newspaper=New York Times | date=August 1, 1991 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/08/01/nyregion/aids-infected-can-question-blood-donors.html?page_wanted=3&src=pm | accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref><ref>Blood Banks Group Must Pay Award in Transfusion Suit, The Record, June 6, 1995</ref><ref>"AIDS Victims Win Fight For Blood Bank Discovery", New Jersey Law Journal. August 8, 1991</ref>

==Nominations==
Baxter was nominated for Trial Lawyer of the Year for his work representing the rights of Health Care Consumers and Patients infected with AIDS by contaminated blood and won several landmark court cases.<ref>[http://www.TLPJ.org Trial Lawyers For Public Justice] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902065209/http://www.tlpj.org/ |date=2011-09-02 }}</ref> "1995 Trial Lawyer of the Year Award Finalists, TLPJ Foundation."<ref>{{Cite news|title=AIDS BEFORE HIGH COURT | newspaper=The Star-Ledger | date=May 7, 1991}}</ref>

