{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}} [[File:1989 CPA 6082.jpg|thumb|right|Founder of Komi literature Ivan Kuratov on the 1989 [[USSR]] commemorative stamp]] '''Ivan Alekseevich Kuratov''' ({{Lang-ru|Иван Алексеевич Куратов}}; {{OldStyleDate|18 July|1839|6 July}} in Kibra village, current Kuratovo village, [[Komi Republic]] &mdash; {{OldStyleDate|29 November|1875|17 November}} in Verny, current [[Almaty]]) was a [[Komis|Komi]] [[poet]] and [[Linguistics|linguist]], seen as renovator of Komi literature.
Kuratov began writing verses at age 13, while studying in a [[seminary]], and was engaged in poetry until his death. The most fruitful period of his life were the years spent in the town of [[Ust-Sysolsk]], where Kuratov settled after unsuccessful attempt to continue his education in Moscow. Here he taught country children, worked on linguistics and wrote poetry. During his lifetime Ivan Kuratov published only five poems, under a pseudonym.
He is the subject of [[Serge Noskov]]'s 2009 opera ''[[Kuratov (opera)|Kuratov]]'', the first in the Komi language.
